Question 2

w_sm <- q1d$weight[q1d$Habit == "Smoker"]
w_nsm <- q1d$weight[q1d$Habit == "NonSmoker"]

hist(w_sm,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "red",
     breaks = 30,
     density = 30, 
     xlab = "Weight (oz)", 
     xlim = range(q1d$weight), 
     las = 1,
     main = "Histogram of Baby Weight\nSplit by Mother's Smoker Status"
)
hist(w_nsm, 
     freq = FALSE, 
     col = "blue", 
     breaks = 30,
     density = 30, 
     angle = -45, 
     add = TRUE
)
lines(density(w_sm), col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
lines(density(w_nsm), col = "blue", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
abline(v = median(w_sm), col = "red", lwd = 2)
abline(v = median(w_nsm), col = "blue", lwd = 2)
legend("topleft",
       legend = c("Weight (Smoker)", "Weight (Non-Smoker)",
                  "Density (Smoker)", "Density (Non-Smoker)",
                  "Median (Smoker)", "Median (Non-Smoker)"),
       fill = c("red", "blue", rep(0, 4)),
       border = c("red", "blue", rep(NA, 4)),
       col = c("red", "blue"), 
       lty = c(NA, NA, 2, 2, 1, 1),
       angle = c(45, -45, rep(NA, 4)), 
       lwd = 2,
       density = c(30, 30, rep(NA, 4)),
       pch = NA,
       inset = 0.05,
       cex = 0.9
)

Based on this graphic, it appears that there is a significant difference between the two groups: the weight of a smokerâ€™s baby is on average lower than that of babies born to non-smokers.

Question 3

(a)

library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.0.5
data(diamonds)
pairs(diamonds[c(1, 5:7)], lower.panel = NULL, pch = ".")

According to the scatterplots, carat and price appear to have the strongest nonlinear relationship, which appears to be logarithmic.

(b)

with(diamonds, {
  plot(price ~ carat, pch = 15, cex = 0.2, col = clarity)
  legend("bottomright", legend = levels(clarity), pch = 15, col = 1:8)
})

Since clarity is a(n) (ordered) factor with 8 levels, col = clarity causes the color for each ordered level to start at 1 and go in whole number sequence up to 8. This is because factors are stored as integers, so col uses the stored integer version (which corresponds to the indices of the levels) of clarity to assign colors. You would see the same result if we used col = as.integer(clarity).

(c)

with(diamonds, {
  plot(price ~ carat, pch = 15, cex = 0.2, col = rainbow(8)[clarity])
  legend("bottomright", legend = levels(clarity), pch = 15, col = rainbow(8))
})

(d)

The higher the order of clarity and amount of carats, the higher price a diamond will have.
